    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/mgf-metadata-completion-from-smiles/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "various open-source tools like XCMS, MZmine 2, MS-DIAL, and in silico fragmentation tools, e.g., MetFrag, MS-FINDER, and SIRIUS 4, have been developed to facilitate and improve the handling of HRMS data in the metabolomics community. Nonetheless, they are, in principle, applicable to the identification of any small molecule. These tools are of major interest for novelty, easy accessibility, and reproducibility. In contrast to vendor software, they are able to leverage publicly available MS/MS libraries like MassBank, RIKEN, and GNPS libraries",
      "asbval:note": "GNPS is mentioned as a publicly available MS/MS library that can be leveraged, but the paper does not describe using GNPS in MGF format or address the issue of missing Molecular Formula fields in GNPS.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-2c05389",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "no",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "mgf-metadata-completion-from-smiles",
